.TH "NODE.CLONENODE" "3JS" "December 1, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Node.cloneNode \- Node: cloneNode() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]cloneNode()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]Node\f[R]
interface returns a duplicate of the node on which this method was
called.
Its parameter controls if the subtree contained in the node is also
cloned or not.
.PP
By default, cloning a node copies all of its attributes and their
values, including event listeners specified via attributes.
By setting the \f[CR]deep\f[R] parameter, you can also copy the subtree
contained in the node.
It does \f[I]not\f[R] copy any other internal data, such as event
listeners added using \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R] or
\f[CR]onevent\f[R] properties (e.g.,
\f[CR]node.onclick = someFunction\f[R]), or the painted image for a
\f[CR]<canvas>\f[R] element.
.PP
The \f[CR]Document.importNode()\f[R] method also creates a copy of a
node.
The difference is that \f[CR]importNode()\f[R] clones the node in the
context of the calling document, whereas \f[CR]cloneNode()\f[R] uses the
document of the node being cloned.
The document context determines the \f[CR]CustomElementRegistry\f[R] for
constructing any custom elements.
For this reason, to clone nodes to be used in another document, use
\f[CR]importNode()\f[R] on the target document.
The \f[CR]HTMLTemplateElement.content\f[R] is owned by a separate
document, so it should also be cloned using
\f[CR]document.importNode()\f[R] so that custom element descendants are
constructed using the definitions in the current document.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] \f[CR]cloneNode()\f[R] may lead to duplicate element
IDs in a document!
If the original node has an \f[CR]id\f[R] attribute, and the clone will
be placed in the same document, then you should modify the clone\(cqs ID
to be unique.
.PP
Also, \f[CR]name\f[R] attributes may need to be modified, depending on
whether duplicate names are expected.
.RE
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
cloneNode()
cloneNode(deep)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]deep\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
If \f[CR]true\f[R], then the node and its whole subtree, including text
that may be in child \f[CR]Text\f[R] nodes, is also copied.
.RS
.PP
If \f[CR]false\f[R] or omitted, only the node will be cloned.
The subtree, including any text that the node contains, is not cloned.
.PP
Note that \f[CR]deep\f[R] has no effect on void elements, such as the
\f[CR]<img>\f[R] and \f[CR]<input>\f[R] elements.
.RE
.SS Return value
The new \f[CR]Node\f[R] cloned.
The cloned node has no parent and is not part of the document,
\f[I]until\f[R] it is added to another node that is part of the
document, using \f[CR]Node.appendChild()\f[R] or a similar method.
.SH EXAMPLE
.SS Using cloneNode()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] p = document.getElementById(\(dqpara1\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] p2 = p.cloneNode(\f[B]true\f[R]);
.EE
.SS Using cloneNode() with templates
Avoid using \f[CR]cloneNode()\f[R] on the content of a
\f[CR]<template>\f[R] element, because if the template contains custom
elements, they will not be upgraded until they are inserted into the
document.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]class\f[R] MyElement \f[B]extends\f[R] HTMLElement {
  constructor() {
    \f[B]super\f[R]();
    console.log(\(dqMyElement created\(dq);
  }
}
customElements.define(\(dqmy\-element\(dq, MyElement);

\f[B]const\f[R] template = document.createElement(\(dqtemplate\(dq);
template.innerHTML = \(ga<my\-element></my\-element>\(ga;

\f[B]const\f[R] clone = template.content.cloneNode(\f[B]true\f[R]);
\f[I]// No log here; my\-element is undefined in the template\(aqs document\f[R]
customElements.upgrade(clone);
\f[I]// Still no log; my\-element is still undefined in the template\(aqs document\f[R]
document.body.appendChild(clone);
\f[I]// Logs \(dqMyElement created\(dq; my\-element is now upgraded\f[R]
.EE
.PP
Instead, use \f[CR]document.importNode()\f[R] to clone the template
content, so that any custom elements are upgraded using the definitions
in the current document:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] clone = document.importNode(template.content, \f[B]true\f[R]);
\f[I]// Logs \(dqMyElement created\(dq; my\-element is upgraded using document\(aqs definitions\f[R]
document.body.appendChild(clone);
.EE
